@NODE "CheckGuide" "CheckGuide by Eddy Carroll"

@{par}          @{fg shine}CheckGuide 1.0 -- Checks AmigaGuide files for common errors
@{par}
@{par}             by Eddy Carroll, September 1994. Freely distributable.@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}Introduction
@{par}
@{par}If you've ever tried creating even a modestly sized AmigaGuide file by hand,
@{par}you'll have discovered that it can be quite difficult to keep track of all the
@{par}various links and cross references. As your help file gets larger, it gets
@{par}increasingly harder to ensure that you have remembered to reference all the
@{par}nodes in the file from at least one place, and haven't left any unresolved
@{par}links.
@{par}
@{par}CheckGuide is a simple utility that can detect several common errors in
@{par}AmigaGuide files. The errors it can detect are:
@{par}
@{par}· Extra plain text between an \@ENDNODE and \@NODE (AmigaGuide won't allow such
@{par}  text to ever be displayed)
@{par}
@{par}· Nodes that are defined but not referenced from any other node. Unless your
@{par}  program directly instructs AmigaGuide to access such nodes, the user won't
@{par}  easily be able to access them.
@{par}
@{par}· Links to help nodes that aren't defined within the file.
@{par}
@{par}· Open braces with no preceding \@ character (usually a simple typo).
@{par}
@{par}· \@{" Button "} constructs with no LINK command (an easy mistake to make if
@{par}  you're entering a lot of them).
@{par}
@{par}All of these options can be selectively enabled or disabled.
@{par}
@{par}        @{fg shine}CheckGuide was used in the creation of @{b}THIS@{ub} document!@{fg text}

@ENDNODE
@NODE AGIX "AGIX by Ralph Seichter"

@{par}          @{fg shine}@{u}From: AGIX.doc 1.2 (5.8.94) Copyright © Ralph Seichter@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg text}PURPOSE:
@{par}
@{par}   Although  AmigaGuide documents may have a node index, only few documents
@{par}make  use of this feature. I suppose that many people are too lazy to build
@{par}an  index  manually (I definitely am), so I thought it would be a good idea
@{par}to have this task done automatically. AGIX scans an AmigaGuide document for
@{par}references  like  \@{"foo" link "bar"} (note that AGIX does not use the node
@{par}definitions), sorts them alphabetically and produces an index file.
@{par}
@{par}   "Haven't I seen something like that before?" you might ask. Well, I have
@{par}seen  one  similar  program  so far, but on my machine it didn't work, so I
@{par}decided  to  try  it myself. The result is short (only 1960 bytes) and uses
@{par}StrnCmp() from locale.library instead of stricmp(), if available, and has a
@{par}very nice sounding name. :)

@ENDNODE
@NODE Installation "CDOpus - Installation"

@{par}See also: @{" Usage " LINK Usage}
@{par}          @{" Examples " LINK Examples}
@{par}          @{" Debug Version " LINK DebugVersion}
@{par}
@{par}@{b}NOTE:@{ub} This is just a @{u}suggestion@{uu} of how to install it. You can do with it
@{par}      what you want, and indeed the program can do @{u}many@{uu} more things than
@{par}      the two things which we'll set-up here.
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Make sure the @{fg fill}"P"@{fg text} bit is set as this program is @{fg shine}'Pure'@{fg text} and may be made
@{par}  @{b}resident@{ub} @{fg fill}(see below)@{fg text}.
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} Protect CDOpus +P @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Copy the main file to @{fg fill}DOpus5:c/@{fg text}
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} Copy CDOpus DOpus5:c/ @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Copy the AmigaGuide to @{fg fill}DOpus5:Help/@{fg text}
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} Copy CDOpus.guide DOpus5:Help/ @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Setup a @{fg shine}"CDO"@{fg text} alias in your shell to CD to the source lister's directory.
@{par}  (Add this to your @{fg fill}S:Shell-Startup@{fg text})
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} Alias CDO "DOpus5:c/CDOpus" @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Setup an @{fg shine}"OCD"@{fg text} alias in your shell to open a new lister in your current dir.
@{par}  (Add this to your @{fg fill}S:Shell-Startup@{fg text})
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} Alias OCD "DOpus5:c/CDOpus OpenLister" @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Read the @{" usage " LINK Usage} and @{" examples " LINK Examples} sections to see what else you can do!
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} If you want to make the command @{b}resident@{ub} (to save loading time), add this
@{par}  line to your @{fg fill}S:User-Startup@{fg text}...
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} Resident DOpus5:c/CDOpus @{bg back}
@{par}  ...and change all the alias commands to reference @{fg fill}"CDOpus"@{fg text} instead of
@{par}  @{fg fill}"DOpus5:c/CDOpus"@{fg text}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Usage "CDOpus - Usage"

@{par}See also: @{" Installation " LINK Installation}
@{par}          @{" Examples " LINK Examples}
@{par}
@{par}The @{fg fill}CDOpus@{fg text} command takes the following command-line parameters:
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}Generic:@{fg text}
@{par} @{" RexxPort   " LINK U_RexxPort}  Specify a differnt @{fg fill}port@{fg text} to talk to, instead of @{fg fill}"DOPUS.1"@{fg text}.
@{par} @{" Help       " LINK U_Help}  @{u}Switch:@{uu} Brings up this text.
@{par}@{fg shine}Modes:@{fg text}  (@{" Description of modes " LINK U_Modes})
@{par} @{bg fill} <DEFAULT>   @{bg back} CD to 'source' lister's path.
@{par} @{bg fill} OpenLister  @{bg back} @{u}Switch:@{uu} Read path into a @{fg fill}new@{fg text} lister.
@{par} @{bg fill} DoAction    @{bg back} @{u}Switch:@{uu} Read path into new @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister.
@{par} @{bg fill} ReadSource  @{bg back} @{u}Switch:@{uu} Read path into the @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister.
@{par} @{bg fill} ReadDest    @{bg back} @{u}Switch:@{uu} Read path into the @{fg fill}'destination'@{fg text} lister.
@{par} @{bg fill} VarSource   @{bg back} @{u}Switch:@{uu} Set @{fg fill}CDOSource@{fg text} environment variable.
@{par} @{bg fill} VarDest     @{bg back} @{u}Switch:@{uu} Set @{fg fill}CDODest@{fg text} environment variable.
@{par}@{fg shine}CD mode only:@{fg back}
@{par} @{" Quiet      " LINK U_Quiet}  @{u}Switch:@{uu} Don't echo the new path to the shell.
@{par}@{fg shine}OpenLister/DoAction/Read modes only:@{fg text}
@{par} @{" NoFront    " LINK U_NoFront}  @{u}Switch:@{uu} Don't pop the @{fg fill}DOpus screen@{fg text} to front.
@{par} @{" Dir        " LINK U_Dir}  Specify a different @{fg fill}dir@{fg text}ectory to read, instead of @{fg fill}<CD>@{fg text}.
@{par}@{fg shine}OpenLister mode only:@{fg text}
@{par} @{" Source     " LINK U_Source}  @{u}Switch:@{uu} Make new lister the @{fg fill}'Source'@{fg text} lister.
@{par} @{" Dest       " LINK U_Dest}  @{u}Switch:@{uu} Make new lister the @{fg fill}'Dest'@{fg text} lister.
@{par} @{" Lock       " LINK U_Lock}  @{u}Switch:@{uu} @{fg fill}Lock@{fg text} new lister as Source/Dest.
@{par}@{fg shine}OpenLister/DoAction modes only:@{fg text}
@{par} @{" Dimensions " LINK U_Dimensions}  Specify different lister @{fg fill}dimensions@{fg text} in x/y/w/h format.
@{par}@{fg shine}DoAction mode only:@{fg text}
@{par} @{" ActPat     " LINK U_ActPat}  Specify files to select.
@{par} @{" ActCom     " LINK U_ActCom}  Specify DOpus5 command to execute.
@{par} @{" ActClose   " LINK U_ActClose}  @{u}Switch:@{uu} Close lister on completion.
@{par}@{fg shine}Read modes only:@{fg text}
@{par} @{" NoNew      " LINK U_NoNew}  @{u}Switch:@{uu} Disable automatic openning of new listers.
@{par}@{fg shine}Var modes only:@{fg text}
@{par} @{" Global     " LINK U_Global}  @{u}Switch:@{uu} Set global variable instead of local.
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}@{u}ReadArgs() Template:@{uu}@{fg text}
@{par}
@{par}RP=REXXPORT/K, HELP/S, QUIET/S, OL=OPENLISTER/S, RS=READSOURCE/S,
RD=READDEST/S, DA=DOACTION/S, NOFRONT/S, NONEW/S, DIR=PATH/K, SOURCE/S,
DEST/S, LOCK/S, POS=DIMENSIONS/K, PAT=ACTPAT/K, COM=ACTCOM/K, ACTCLOSE/S,
VARSOURCE/S, VARDEST/S, GLOBAL/S

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_ActPat "CDOpus - Usage, ActPat"
@{par}See also: @{" Examples " LINK Examples}
@{par}          @{" ActCom " LINK U_ActCom}
@{par}          @{" ActClose " LINK U_ActClose}
@{par}
@{par}Listers openned in @{" DoAction-mode " LINK U_Modes} can have some or all of their files
@{b}selected@{ub} by giving any valid @{fg fill}AmigaDOS pattern@{fg text} to the @{fg fill}ActPat@{fg text} keyword.
Note that the @{fg fill}ActPat@{fg text} keyword is entirely @{i}optional @{ui}-- you can execute an
Opus @{" command " LINK U_ActCom} without selecting any files.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_ActCom "CDOpus - Usage, ActCom"
@{par}See also: @{" Examples " LINK Examples}
@{par}          @{" ActPat " LINK U_ActPat}
@{par}          @{" ActClose " LINK U_ActClose}
@{par}
@{par}When in @{" DoAction-mode " LINK U_Modes}, the @{fg fill}ActCom@{fg text} keyword takes the name of one of
the @{fg fill}internal DOpus commands@{fg text} (you know -- "@{fg fill}Delete@{fg text}", "@{fg fill}All@{fg text}", "@{fg fill}SmartRead@{fg text}", and
so on). The newly openned lister will be in @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} mode, and the command
will be executed @{b}after@{ub} @{fg fill}file selection@{fg text} (if any) by the @{" ActPat " LINK U_ActPat} keyword.
For commands like "@{fg fill}Delete@{fg text}" and "@{fg fill}SmartRead@{fg text}" you will want to select some
files first, but for other commands such as "@{fg fill}All@{fg text}" and "@{fg fill}CacheList@{fg text}" there
is no need. Like the @{" ActPat " LINK U_ActPat} keyword, @{fg fill}ActCom@{fg text} is entirely @{i}optional @{ui}--
you can open a lister and select some files without having to execute
a command.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_ActClose "CDOpus - Usage, ActClose"

@{par}See also: @{" ActPat " LINK U_ActPat}
@{par}          @{" ActCom " LINK U_ActCom}
@{par}
@{par}When @{fg fill}CDOpus@{fg text} is in @{" DoAction-mode " LINK U_Modes}, the @{fg fill}ActClose@{fg text} switch causes it to
@{b}automatically close@{ub} the new lister once the @{" file selection " LINK U_ActPat} and @{" command " LINK U_ActCom} 
have completed.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_Global "CDOpus - Usage, Global"

@{par}By default, @{fg fill}environment variables@{fg text} created in @{" Var-mode " LINK U_Modes} are @{b}local@{ub} to the
current shell, meaning they only exist for programs run from the same
shell. The @{fg fill}Global@{fg text} switch causes @{fg fill}CDOpus@{fg text} to create @{b}global@{ub} variables instead
(stored in @{fg fill}ENV:@{fg text} with all versions of AmigaDOS upto 3.1) which are
available to all programs running on the machine.
@{par}
@{par}If you don't understand what all this means, it probably isn't of much
use to you anyway.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_RexxPort "CDOpus - Usage, RexxPort"

@{par}See also: @{" Examples " LINK Examples}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}RexxPort@{fg text} is an optional @{b}keyword@{ub} which lets you specify the name of the
ARexx port to talk to. By default this is @{fg fill}"DOPUS.1"@{fg text} (most of the time
you'll only be running one copy of DOpus), but should you need to address
another name you can use this.
@{par}
@{par}@{b}NOTE:@{ub} Port names are @{u}case-sensitive@{uu}.
@{par}
@{par}When running @{fg fill}CDOpus@{fg text} from @{fg fill}Directory Opus@{fg text}, you should @{u}always@{uu} specify the
Rexx port in case one day you run two copies. To do this you should have...
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} ... RexxPort {Qp} ... @{bg back}
@{par}...on the command-line.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_Help "CDOpus - Usage, Help"

@{par}Seel also: @{" Future " LINK Future}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}Help@{fg text} is a @{b}switch@{ub} which will dump the help-text to the shell window when
given.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_Quiet "CDOpus - Usage, Quiet"

@{par}See also: @{" Modes " LINK U_Modes}
@{par}
@{par}Normally, in @{" CD-Mode " LINK U_Modes}, the name of the new path is echoed to the shell
before the actual directory change takes place. If the @{fg fill}Quiet@{fg text} @{b}switch@{ub} is
given this doesn't happen.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_NoFront "CDOpus - Usage, NoFront"

@{par}By default, when one of @{fg fill}OpenLister@{fg text}, @{fg fill}DoAction@{fg text}, @{fg fill}ReadSource@{fg text}, or @{fg fill}ReadDest@{fg text} is
in effect, the @{fg fill}DOpus screen@{fg text} will be popped to the front as you probably want to see
want to see and use your newly created/pathed lister. If you specify the
@{fg fill}NoFront@{fg text} @{b}switch@{ub} on the command-line the screens are left alone.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_NoNew "CDOpus - Usage, NoNew"

@{par}By default, when @{fg fill}ReadSource@{fg text} or @{fg fill}ReadDest@{fg text} looks for a lister and one of
the desired type doesn't exist, a new lister is @{i}automatically openned.@{ui} This
behaviour is similar to the internal @{fg fill}DOpus@{fg text} commands and can be very useful
- however, there may be times when it isn't desireable. If you use the
@{fg fill}NoNew@{fg text} switch you'll get an @{fg fill}error-requester@{fg text} instead of a new lister.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_Dir "CDOpus - Usage, Dir"

@{par}See also: @{" Dimensions " LINK U_Dimensions}
@{par}
@{par}By default, when one of @{fg fill}OpenLister@{fg text}, @{fg fill}DoAction@{fg text}, @{fg fill}ReadSource@{fg text}, or @{fg fill}ReadDest@{fg text} is
in effect, a lister will read in the current directory of your shell. You
can use the @{fg fill}Dir@{fg text} @{b}keyword@{ub} to specify a different directory to read in, making
it very useful for @{fg fill}DOpus@{fg text}-buttons which open listers with different sizes
and positions for specific paths (see @{" examples " LINK Examples}).

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_Source "CDOpus - Usage, Source"

@{par}See also: @{" Dest " LINK U_Dest}
@{par}          @{" Lock " LINK U_Lock}
@{par}
@{par}By default, new listers created with the @{fg fill}OpenLister@{fg text} command are in @{fg fill}'off'@{fg text} 
mode. The @{fg fill}Source@{fg text} switch puts them in @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} mode.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_Dest "CDOpus - Usage, Dest"

@{par}See also: @{" Source " LINK U_Source}
@{par}          @{" Lock " LINK U_Lock}
@{par}
@{par}By default, new listers created with the @{fg fill}OpenLister@{fg text} command are in @{fg fill}'off'@{fg text} 
mode. The @{fg fill}Dest@{fg text} switch puts them in @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} mode.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_Lock "CDOpus - Usage, Lock"

@{par}See also: @{" Source " LINK U_Source}
@{par}          @{" Dest " LINK U_Dest}
@{par}
@{par}When used in combination with the @{" Source " LINK U_Source} and @{" Dest " LINK U_Dest} switches, the @{fg fill}Lock@{fg text}
switch can put a newly created lister into @{fg fill}'locked-source'@{fg text} or @{fg fill}'locked-dest'@{fg text} 
mode.

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_Dimensions "CDOpus - Usage, Dimensions"

@{par}By default, new listers created with @{fg fill}OpenLister@{fg text} or @{fg fill}DoAction@{fg text} open under
your mouse-pointer with either the default size you set in your
@{fg fill}DOpus environment @{fg text}file (DOpus 5.11 and above only), or the size defined by
the path's @{fg fill}icon@{fg text}, if it has one. The @{fg fill}Dimensions@{fg text} keyword can be used to set
a different size and position for the lister.
@{par}
@{par}The format is @{fg fill}<x-pos>@{fg text}/@{fg fill}<y-pos>@{fg text}/@{fg fill}<width>@{fg text}/@{fg fill}<height>@{fg text}, e.g. 50/10/100/200
@{par}
@{par}@{b}NOTE: @{ub}Specifying 0/0/@{fg fill}<w>@{fg text}/@{fg fill}<h>@{fg text} will make the lister open under the mouse in
@{par}      the current version of @{fg fill}Directory Opus@{fg text} (5.11). This means that it is
@{par}      not possible to open a lister in the top corner of the screen. @{bg shine}:-(@{bg back}

@ENDNODE
@NODE U_Modes "CDOpus - Usage, Modes"

@{par}See also: @{" Usage " LINK Usage}
@{par}          @{" Examples " LINK Examples}

@{par}@{fg shine}@{u}CD-Mode@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}This is the @{b}default@{ub} mode and is used whenever none of the other modes are
specified. In @{fg fill}CD-Mode@{fg text} the program will attempt to change your shell's
current directory to that of the current DOpus @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister.
@{par}
@{par}In this mode, all error messages go to the @{b}shell window@{ub}, while in all other
modes error messages appear in @{b}requesters@{ub}.
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}@{u}OpenLister-Mode@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}This mode is enabled when the @{" OpenLister " LINK Usage} switch is given on the
command-line. In @{fg fill}OpenLister-Mode@{fg text} a @{b}new@{ub} lister is created on the DOpus
screen. This lister can be made to read your shell's current directory,
@{b}or@{ub} another directory given on the command-line. You can also specify
the @{b}size@{ub} and @{b}position@{ub} of the lister and determine whether it will be
in @{fg fill}'off'@{fg text}, @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text}, @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text}, @{fg fill}'locked-source'@{fg text} or, @{fg fill}'locked-dest'@{fg text} @{b}mode@{ub}.
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}@{u}DoAction-Mode@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}This mode is enabled when the @{" DoAction " LINK Usage} switch is given. A new @{fg fill}'source'
@{fg text}lister for the @{fg fill}current directory@{fg text} (unless another is @{" specified " LINK U_Dir}) will open
and it is possible to give an AmigaDOS @{" pattern " LINK U_ActPat} and a DOpus5 @{" command " LINK U_ActCom} so
that all files matching that pattern have the command performed on them.
You don't have to give either the pattern or the command (you could just
select some files, for example, or just issue a command like @{fg fill}"all"@{fg text}), and
you can have the lister @{" close " LINK U_ActClose} automatically once the command has
completed.
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}@{u}ReadSource-Mode@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}This mode is enabled when the @{" ReadSource " LINK Usage} switch is given on the
command-line. In @{fg fill}ReadSource-Mode@{fg text} the current DOpus @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister
will read in either a named directory @{b}or@{ub} your shell's current directory.
@{par}
@{par}Unless you use the @{" NoNew " LINK U_NoNew} switch, a new @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister will be @{b}openned
@{b}automatically@{ub} if one doesn't already exist.
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}@{u}ReadDest-Mode@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}This mode is the same as the @{fg fill}ReadSource-Mode@{fg text}, but it affects the
@{fg fill}'destination'@{fg text} lister instead of the @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} one.
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}@{u}VarSource-Mode@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}This mode is enabled when the @{" VarSource " LINK Usage} switch is given. @{fg fill}CDOpus@{fg text} will
create an @{fg fill}environment variable@{fg text} called @{fg shine}CDOSource@{fg text} containing the @{b}path@{ub} of
the @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister. By default the variable is @{b}local@{ub} to the shell, but
it can be made @{" global " LINK U_Global}. If you don't know what @{fg fill}environment variables@{fg text} 
are or how they can be useful, I suggest you read a good AmigaDOS
manual, @{fg shine}:-)@{fg text}.
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}@{u}VarDest-Mode@{fg text}@{uu}
@{par}
@{par}This mode is the same as the @{fg fill}VarSource-Mode@{fg text}, but it creates a variable
called @{fg shine}CDODest@{fg text} with the @{fg fill}'destination'@{fg text} lister's path instead.
@{par}

@ENDNODE
@NODE Examples "CDOpus - Examples"

@{par}See also: @{" Usage " LINK Usage}
@{par}
@{par}Here are some quick examples of how to use the program:
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Shell Alias to CD to the @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister's path.
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} Alias CDO "DOpus5:c/CDOpus" @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Shell Alias to CD to the @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister's path, for a @{b}second@{ub} @{fg fill}DOpus5@{fg text}.
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} Alias CDO2 "DOpus5:c/CDOpus RexxPort DOPUS.2" @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Shell Alias to open a @{b}new@{ub} lister with the same path as the shell.
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} Alias OCD "DOpus5:c/CDOpus OpenLister" @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}As above@{ub}, but make it the @{fg fill}'dest'@{fg text} lister as well.
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} Alias OCDest "DOpus5:c/CDOpus OpenLister Dest" @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Shell Alias to read the current directory into the @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister.
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} Alias Source "DOpus5:c/CDOpus ReadSource" @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} DOpus button to open a @{fg fill}'source'@{fg text} lister in @{fg fill}"RAM:Env"@{fg text}, with given @{fg fill}size@{fg text}.
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} AmigaDOS @{bg back}
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} DOpus5:c/CDOpus RexxPort {Qp} OpenLister Source Dir RAM:Env Dimensions 11/3/100/50 @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Shell Alias to have @{fg fill}DOpus@{fg text} @{b}HexRead #?.exe@{ub} in the @{fg fill}current dir@{fg text}.
@{par}@{fg fill}>@{fg text} @{bg fill} Alias HexRead "DOpus5:c/CDOpus DoAction ActPat #?.exe ActCom HexRead" @{bg back}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}Hope you get the idea!?@{fg text}

@ENDNODE
@NODE DebugVersion "CDOpus - Debug Version"

@{par}As well as the main @{fg fill}"CDOpus"@{fg text} executable file, you should also find a file
called @{fg fill}"CDOpus_DEBUG"@{fg text}. The two programs are identical apart from:
@{par}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} The @{b}debug@{ub} version contains all the @{fg fill}debug labels@{fg text} and @{fg fill}headers@{fg text}.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} The @{b}debug@{ub} version outputs some extra information while it is running.
@{par}  (Most of the time it just reports the commands sent to the @{fg fill}DOpus ARexx
@{par}  port @{fg text}and what the results are).
@{par}
@{par}If you have any problems getting things to work, you should try running
the @{b}debug@{ub} version and see if you can see what's going on. If there appears
to be a @{b}bug@{ub} in the program, @{" reporting " LINK Credits} what the @{b}debug@{ub} version outputs could
help me a great deal in working out what is going wrong.

@ENDNODE
@NODE History "CDOpus - History"

@{par}See also: @{" Future " LINK Future}
@{par}
@{par}@{b}NOTE:@{ub} Versions numbering is in the @{fg shine}<version>@{fg fill}.@{fg shine}<revision>@{fg text} format. This means
@{par}      that version @{fg shine}1.10 @{fg text}(one.ten) is @{b}newer@{ub} than version @{fg shine}1.2 @{fg text}(one.two).
@{par}
@{par}@{u}@{fg shine} v1.1 (Private release) - ??-Aug-1995 @{uu}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}First@{ub} release for testing.
@{par}
@{par}@{u}@{fg shine} v1.2 (Private release) - 16-Aug-1995 @{uu}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Reorganised a lot of the code.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Added @{" Source " LINK U_Source}, @{" Dest " LINK U_Dest} and, @{" Lock " LINK U_Lock} @{b}switches@{ub}.
@{par}
@{par}@{u}@{fg shine} v1.3 (Private release) - 19-Aug-1995 @{uu}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} More code reorganisation.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Removed @{fg fill}"Reqs"@{fg text} switch - @{b}requesters@{ub} are turned on @{u}automatically@{uu} unless
@{par}  in @{fg fill}CD-mode@{fg text} where error messages go to the @{b}shell@{ub}.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Added @{" ReadSource " LINK Usage} and, @{" ReadDest " LINK Usage} @{b}switches@{ub}.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} W@{fg fill}r@{fg shine}o@{fg fill}t@{fg text}e @{bg fill}t@{bg shine}h@{bg fill}i@{bg shine}s@{bg back} @{b}A@{ub}@{u}m@{uu}@{b}i@{ub}@{u}g@{uu}@{b}a@{ub}@{u}G@{uu}@{b}u@{ub}@{u}i@{uu}@{b}d@{ub}@{u}e@{uu}.
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}@{u} v1.4 (Private release) - 21-Aug-1995 @{uu}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Fixed@{ub} a few minor mistakes in the AmigaGuide, added a couple more links
@{par}  and a little more colour in places. Updated the @{" Credits " LINK Credits} node.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Fixed@{ub} something in the way that @{fg fill}ARexx@{fg text} messages are sent to @{fg fill}DOpus5@{fg text}.
@{par}  (This shouldn't have caused any problems, but it is done properly now).
@{par}
@{par}@{u}@{fg shine} v1.5 (Private release) - 27-Aug-1995 @{uu}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Added@{ub} my @{b}new@{ub} @{fg fill}email address@{fg text} to the @{" credits " LINK Credits} node.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Added@{ub} an @{fg fill}icon@{fg text} for this 'guide. (@{" Thanks Trevor! " LINK Credits})
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Fixed@{ub} alphabetical-sorting in the @{" credits " LINK Credits} node. (@{" Thanks Trevor! " LINK Credits})
@{par}
@{par}@{u}@{fg shine} v1.6 (MWB_DOpus_7.lha release) - 10-Sep-1995 @{uu}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{i}Where useful, @{ui}new listers will open @{b}automatically@{ub} if there isn't a lister
@{par}  of the required type open already (just like @{fg fill}DOpus5's@{fg text} internal commands).
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Added@{ub} @{" NoNew " LINK U_NoNew} @{b}switch@{ub} to disable the above feature.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Added a new @{" known bug " LINK Future}, which isn't my fault. :)
@{par}
@{par}@{u}@{fg shine} v1.7 - 6-Jan-1996 @{uu}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Added@{ub} @{" VarSource " LINK Usage} and @{" VarDest " LINK Usage} commands and accompanying @{" Global " LINK U_Global} switch.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Added@{ub} @{" DoAction " LINK Usage} command and accompanying switches @{" ActPat " LINK U_ActPat}, @{" ActCom " LINK U_ActCom}, and
@{par}  @{" ActClose " LINK U_ActClose}. @{" Thanks " LINK Credits} to Dave Clarke for the suggestion.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Rearranged@{ub} the @{" Usage " LINK Usage} section a little, hopefully it's better now.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Removed@{ub} section about possible @{fg fill}enforcer hits@{fg text}, they were nothing to
@{par}  do with my programs (YIPEE!).
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Updated@{ub} @{" Credits " LINK Credits} section. (Most importantly my @{b}new EMail/WWW addresses@{ub}).
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} @{b}Added@{ub} EMail address and WWW URL for @{" Children of the Storm " LINK COTS_Charity}.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} This should be the last @{fg fill}DOpusFuncs@{fg text} update before @{fg fill}DOpus 5.2@{fg text} is released.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Hey! It's my birthday tomorrow!... :-)

@Remark VERSION NUMBERS/DATES: VER string and Contents Node.
@Remark WHEN ADDING NEW NODES, DON'T FORGET TO UPDATE THE INDEX.

@ENDNODE
@NODE Future "CDOpus - Future & Known Bugs"

@{par}See also: @{" History " LINK History}
@{par}          @{" Credits " LINK Credits}
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}@{u} To Do: @{uu}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Make the @{" help " LINK U_Help} text pause if the shell window is not tall enough.
@{par}  (This turns out to be much more of a pain in the arse than expected!
@{par}  In fact, I really can't be fucked to learn how to do lowish-level IO
@{par}  with the console.device just for this... Ugh, why couldn't it be simple!)
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} If you want something, @{" ask " LINK Credits} for it!
@{par}
@{par}@{fg shine}@{u} Known Bugs: @{uu}
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} Under @{fg fill}Directory Opus 5.11@{fg text} it is not possible to open new listers in the
@{par}  top-right corner, because the coordinates @{fg shine}0/0@{fg text} make the lister open under
@{par}  the mouse pointer.
@{par}@{fg fill}o@{fg text} There is a bug in the @{fg fill}OS3.1 AmigaGuide@{fg text} which can cause extra spaces,
@{par}  missing spaces, and duplicated words at @{fg fill}line-wraps@{fg text}. @{b}This it not my fault!@{ub}

